
                                            An Iraqi army helicopter crashed during a routine flight on Sunday, killing all seven people on board.
                                         BAGHDAD - An Iraqi army helicopter crashed during a routine flight on Sunday, killing all seven people on board, a military statement and Iraqi air force officers said. The Russian-made Mi-17 helicopter went down near the southern province of Kut, the statement said. Two pilots and five army officers were killed, Iraqi air force officers told Reuters. A technical malfunction caused the crash, the military statement said. Iraq is slowly rebuilding its air force, once one of the worldâ€™s largest, after the US-led invasion that toppled Saddam Hussein in 2003.